message:
@waderoush The difference between them is that Quora is for building a corpus of knowlege whereas convore is for fostering real time topic related communication. Those are two completely different things, like radio and tv. 

I use convore for quick comments. I invest much more time into quora responses as the stakes at quora are significantly higher, after all the industry is relatively small (less than 150.000 players) which means that every single post on quora might have impact on my career. I see convore as a replacement for IRC, fire and forget style, quick on the fly topic conversation, not as messy as twitter but real communication. 

What I hope for is that convore becomes a SAAS company that offers white label real time community services that can be integrated into websites. That would be a way for them to become quite big if they do it right (the whitelabel is really important here, pricing too of course)

@craigshipp I really see this part as key: "All we need now is a lot of users and we've got something."

It seems like after the initial rush from when Convore first launched, there aren't nearly as many new members and things have just been slowing down since not everyone from the initial rush decided to stick around. They need a way to start attracting new users to build up the numbers. More users = more outlets for conversation = more activity on the site.

I'm currently in 20 groups. During the first few weeks, if I went for a day without checking Convore my unread messages would be 300+. Now I can go for a few days without looking and that number still won't hit 100. That needs to change.

